snippet.textDisplay: In regards to the topic of what Ninja said, funny enough my opinion on the matter is largely motivated by the movie "whiplash". I don't think "anger" is always the right move but failure is what separates the great from the normal. The best people in their respective fields experience failures in their careers and their ambitions. The difference is exactly what J.K. Simmons character said in the film, that someone who wishes to be "great" or be one of the best in their field "would not be discouraged". I have talked with people with differing views about the film and its message, always finding myself enlightened opposing points of views and experiences but personally, can't help but agree with the message of sacrifice, self-punishment, and determination (no matter the obstacle) that the movie, and perhaps Ninja's tweet reinforces. IF and this is as big if you want to be the absolute best in your field, it requires sacrifice. It requires pain. It requires overcoming potentially unimaginable failures time and time again in pursuit of your goal because you will not quit. That is what makes the greats just that. The resentment of their own failure that makes them better. I believe that the people that are judging Tyler Blevins' words are those who may not have his same dedication to performative ability when it comes to video games, but likely have it elsewhere and are just unable to equivalate his (Tyler Blevins) ambitions and strife to their own. I do think he should have acknowledged the fact that it by no means guarantee's success but rather that it is what those who wish to be the best have to do to ensure that someone else doesn't surpass them, but don't think that his tweets and what he said in them are wrong or are damaging. They are mentalities that are held by many other people who are considered the greatest in their fields. Example: Kobe Bryant in regards to his practice routine saying that if you aren't practicing with the same or more competitive nature as you play with during a game, then you will never become the best you can be, and I can't help but think that mindset/mentality translates across most anything that can be considered competitive.

snippet.textDisplay: Hot take: it wasn't Zimmerman's fault entirely that he killed Trayvon Martin. Now, it was entirely wrong and unjustifiable to go that far and he should be held accountable, I actually think he should've been sentenced. However, this acute prejudice he obviously acted on in this situation wasn't because cops are bad in general or because he's a white supremacist, I don't think he was even inherently racist. He acted on an acute prejudice that I think most people have subconsciously that they don't even recognize. It's simply how people are expected to think, despite it being wrong. So I don't think Zimmerman deserved to be slammed by those politicians directly and be called a racist or white supremacist. I think they should have used that case as an example of a wide scale problem of social prejudice instead of claiming he's a terrible person. His lawsuit is ridiculous and it shows he's an asshole who doesn't care for what he did, and like I said, he deserves to serve time. He didn't kill Martin because he hates black people, but he did let prejudice get in the way of his decision making and that led him to murder a young man who didn't deserve to be murdered and he should be punished accordingly.
snippet.textOriginal: Hot take: it wasn't Zimmerman's fault *entirely* that he killed Trayvon Martin. Now, it was entirely wrong and unjustifiable to go that far and he should be held accountable, I actually think he should've been sentenced. However, this acute prejudice he obviously acted on in this situation wasn't because cops are bad in general or because he's a white supremacist, I don't think he was even inherently racist. He acted on an acute prejudice that I think most people have subconsciously that they don't even recognize. It's simply how people are expected to think, despite it being wrong. So I don't think Zimmerman deserved to be slammed by those politicians directly and be called a racist or white supremacist. I think they should have used that case as an example of a wide scale problem of social prejudice instead of claiming he's a terrible person. His lawsuit is ridiculous and it shows he's an asshole who doesn't care for what he did, and like I said, he deserves to serve time. He didn't kill Martin because he hates black people, but he did let prejudice get in the way of his decision making and that led him to murder a young man who didn't deserve to be murdered and he should be punished accordingly.
